{:itonami.blueprint/id "cloud-itonami-isic-3319"
 :itonami.blueprint/name "Repair of Other Equipment"
 :itonami.blueprint/isic-rev5 "3319"
 :itonami.blueprint/domain :manufacturing/other-equipment-repair
 :itonami.blueprint/license "AGPL-3.0-or-later"
 :itonami.blueprint/social-impact [:worker-safety :repair-access :circular-economy-repair-over-replace]
 :itonami.blueprint/governor :other-equipment-repair-governor
 :itonami.blueprint/robotics false
 :itonami.blueprint/required-technologies [:identity :forms :audit-ledger]
 :itonami.blueprint/optional-technologies []
 :itonami.blueprint/status :public-oss
 :itonami.blueprint/maturity :implemented
 :itonami.blueprint/implemented-slice
 "`:other-equipment-repair-governor` is implemented end-to-end in
 `src/other_equipment_repair` as a REPAIR-SHOP OPERATIONS COORDINATION
 actor -- Repair Advisor (LLM proposal-only) ⊣ Repair Governor (closed-
 op-allowlist / equipment-verification / legal-basis / unresolved-concern
 hard-gates). ISIC 3319 is the RESIDUAL repair-services class -- repair
 of miscellaneous equipment not covered by the more specific repair
 classes 3311 (fabricated metal products), 3312 (machinery and
 equipment), 3313 (electronic and optical equipment), 3314 (electrical
 equipment) or 3315 (transport equipment). This actor deliberately holds
 NO repair-equipment/diagnostic-tool control authority and NO
 return-to-service sign-off authority (both are HARD, permanent governor
 blocks, never overridable by human approval -- see
 `other-equipment-repair.governor` ns docstring), the SAME coordination-
 only, narrower-than-4211 shape `cloud-itonami-isic-3320` (Installation
 of Industrial Machinery and Equipment) already established in this
 fleet. Every one of its four proposal ops (`:log-repair-record` /
 `:schedule-repair-operation` / `:flag-safety-concern` / `:order-
 supplies`) carries `:effect :propose` ONLY -- the governor HARD-holds
 any proposal that doesn't (`effect-not-propose-violations`), a
 structural invariant distinguishing this actor from siblings that DO
 commit real-world actuation effects.

 UNLIKE `cloud-itonami-isic-3320` (whose `:schedule-installation-
 operation` ALWAYS escalates to a human, at every phase, because it
 coordinates potential heavy-lift/rigging-equipment dispatch), THIS
 actor's `:schedule-repair-operation` MAY auto-commit at phase 3 when the
 governor is clean -- repair-of-other-equipment is the ISIC-residual,
 lower-average-physical-risk class (furniture, sporting/recreational
 goods, musical instruments, miscellaneous equipment n.e.c.), and only
 `:flag-safety-concern` is a permanent, unconditional `high-stakes`
 member in `other-equipment-repair.governor`. This is a deliberate,
 narrower escalation surface than 3320's, not an oversight -- see
 `other-equipment-repair.phase` ns docstring 'Actuation' section.

 Per-jurisdiction (JPN/USA/DEU) pre-repair hazard/energy-control
 legal-basis catalog (`other-equipment-repair.facts`) with real official
 sources -- all THREE seeded jurisdictions are honestly `:qualitative`
 here (a procedural stop-machine/lockout-tagout/qualified-personnel duty
 before cleaning, inspection or repair work, not a fixed numeric
 notice-lead-time), unlike `cloud-itonami-isic-3320`'s catalog, which
 found ONE `:quantitative` jurisdiction (JPN) for a DIFFERENT proposal
 type (an installation-notification PLAN filing) -- this actor does not
 invent a lead-time count where none of its three researched
 jurisdictions' repair/maintenance safety law gives one for repair work
 itself. This build ships NO JVM-only interop anywhere in `src/` (no
 real Resend/Twilio transports -- `other-equipment-repair.notify` ships
 only the portable mock notifier + `Notifier` protocol seam) per this
 workspace's cljs-first `.cljc` runtime-priority rule. `:flag-safety-
 concern` ALWAYS escalates to a human, at every phase, unconditionally.
 See `docs/` -- README `Actuation` section -- for the full governor-check
 enumeration and the rationale for each hard/soft rule."}
